	(1514,0,'2017-12-17 07:26:02','2017-12-17 07:26:02','<p><strong><em>In his autobiography, businessman Ly Qui Trung told the readers about his risky decisions when he was the general director of a hotel Saigon.</em></strong></p>\n\n<p><em>I officially became the General Director of Saigon Star Hotel in the age of 30. At that time, I had nothing to lose and nothing not to dare to do</em> - Ly Qui Trung bared his thoughts in his autobiography &ldquo;The sky is not only blue&quot;.</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://wordpress49.local/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/644958637724858312-ly-quy-trung.png\" style=\"height: 432px; width: 650px;\" /></p>\n\n<p><em>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Businessman Ly Qui Trung</em></p>\n\n<p><strong>Being a general director in an extremely difficult circumstance</strong></p>\n\n<p>1997 was the most difficult year, when the economic crisis in Southeast Asia broke out, leading to a series of consequences. People hardly traveled and hotels was unable to adapt to the sudden shortage of tourists, resulting in losses and bankruptcy.</p>\n\n<p><em>I still remember, the New World &ndash; the largest hotel at that time had to dismiss hundreds of employees to cut down cost. The price of Saigon Star Hotel&rsquo;s room fell down from 60-70 USD/night to below 20 USD/night. However, there was still no guest</em> - Mr. Trung recalled.</p>\n\n<p><em>Businessman Ly Qui Trung - co-founder of Pho 24</em></p>\n\n<p>Becoming the director in an extremely difficult situation, both from economic circumstances and internal problems of the hotel , many people advised Mr. Trung to refuse that position. But Mr. Trung saw other potentials.</p>\n\n<p><em>I felt that was a fun battlefield. I thought if I failed, I would still be very proud and confident becaue I dared to face with challenge. And more importantly, I would learn many useful lessons if the failure happened.</em></p>\n\n<p><strong>How to receive respect from the elders?</strong></p>\n\n<p>The first challenge of&nbsp; being the general manager was how to receive respect from the staffs, &nbsp;who were especially older and more experienced than a boss who was only 30. Everyone knew that this young man had not managed any hotel before. This hindered Mr. Trung from creating his credibility with his colleagues or subordinates.</p>\n\n<p>Even in the officical meeting with the Executive Board, some people also &nbsp;suggested that new general manager could do whatever he wanted but should not change the recent system of organizations as well as existing business direction of the hotel.</p>\n\n<p><em>If I shouldn&rsquo;t change anything, does it mean that I will become the bodyguard of this hotel?</em> Trung tried to remain calm and slowly replied: <em>I do not accept that. I have plans and I will do anything in order to change the current situations of this hotel, even change the key personnel if necessary. That is why people recruited me.</em></p>\n\n<p>After that statement, the following comments from other chiefs seemed to&nbsp; be more gentle and cooperating. Mr. Trung won the &ldquo;first round&rdquo; and received credibility from his collegues.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Not being a traditional director</strong></p>\n\n<p>Step into a new environment with much pressure from inside and outside, he chose a wise decision that later contributed to his future success: Not being a traditional director.</p>\n\n<p>So, instead of being a powerful and noble boss, Mr. Trung ate with his staffs in the canteen. <em>To build trust in employees, a director need not only closeness and friendliness, but also a real sincerity that no one can act.</em> Trung affirmed.</p>\n\n<p>Mr. Trung realized that having intimacy with customers was even harder than being close with staffs. Thus, Mr. Trung decided to move his office to be near the front desk, from where he could easily see what happened each day in the reception area. This is where most customers have their first impression, and is also believed, according to the term &quot;The Moment of Truth&quot; or defining moment, to be the place that decideds the possibility of customers&rsquo; return.</p>\n\n<p><strong>The customer is not always right!</strong></p>\n\n<p>The new office position allowed customer to meet the director when they want easier. <em>I think that all complaints are rewarding and they give this hotel a chance to perfect. The danger is when the customer is not satisfied and quietly walked away, </em>Mr.Trung confided.</p>\n\n<p>Moreover, owing to the new office location, Mr. Trung had the opportunity to deal with a foreign visitor that he refused to serve for the first and only time in his life. The reason was that this visitor was very rude and often said offensive words to the hotel staff. The hotel staffs were all very afraid of this guy.</p>\n\n<p>After much effort from Mr. Trung, from the meeting in person to sending letters in the most polite way, ultimately, even the customer is a VIP, Mr. Trung refused to serve.</p>\n\n<p><em>I have drawn an experience that the phare &#39;customer is always right&quot; is not always true, especially when customers become&#39; ridiculous&#39; dismissively.</em> Trung concluded.</p>\n\n<p><em style=\"line-height: 1.4;\">The title is renamed by hoteliers.vn.</em></p>\n\n<p><em>Source: Kien Anh - &nbsp;Trithuctre Magazine</em></p>\n\n<p><em>Translator: B.H.D</em></p>\n','Businessman Ly Qui Trung: Dare to change, dare to succeed','','publish','open','open','','businessman-ly-qui-trung-dare-to-change-dare-to-succeed','','','2017-12-17 07:26:02','2017-12-17 07:26:02','',0,'http://wordpress49.local/?p=1514',0,'post','',0),
